   Since you are building a tool designed to integrate with Canvas, your distribution strategy needs to balance **security** (protecting those API keys), **accessibility** (how teachers open the app), and **maintenance** (how you push updates).

Here is a breakdown of the best ways to distribute your new system.

---
## Distribution Comparison Table

| Method | Best For... | Setup Difficulty | Teacher Effort |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **LTI** | Institutional Adoption | High | Low (Built into Canvas) |
| **Heroku** | Centralized Hosting | Medium | Low (Just a URL) |
| **Git** | Developer Backup | Low | High (They must host it) |
| **Extension** | Individual Power-Users | Medium | Medium (Must install) |

---

### My Recommendation: The "Professional" Stack

1. **Git:** Keep your code in a private GitHub repo.
2. **Heroku:** Deploy your code there so you have a live URL.
3. **LTI:** Configure Canvas to point to that Heroku URL as an LTI tool.